NASA astronaut Christina Koch handles media bags that enable the manufacturing of organ-like tissues using the BioFabrication Facility (BFF), a 3-D biological printer aboard the International Space Station. The BFF could become a part of a larger system capable of manufacturing whole, fully-functioning human organs from existing patient cells in microgravity.

Expedition 61 Flight Engineers (clockwise from bottom) Andrew Morgan and Jessica Meir of NASA and cosmonaut Oleg Skripochka of Roscosmos brush up on their emergency response skills. The three crewmates practiced quickly entering their Soyuz crew ship and simulated emergency undocking and descent procedures in the unlikely event they would need to evacuate the station. #nasa #roscosmos #astronaut #cosmonaut #international #space #station

The Boeing #Starliner crew ship atop a United Launch Alliance Atlas V rocket rolled out to the launch pad in Florida today. It's uncrewed Orbital Flight Test launch to the space station is targeted for Friday, Dec. 20, at 6:36 a.m. EST. Starliner will arrive at the station on Saturday for an automated docking at 8:27 a.m. (Pic 1) NASA's Commercial Crew Program astronauts (from left) Nicole Mann, Michael Fincke, Suni Williams, Josh Cassada, and Eric Boe pose for a picture with Boeingâ€™s CST-100 Starliner spacecraft behind them. Astronauts Andrew Morgan and Luca Parmitano wrapped up a 6-hour and 33-minute spacewalk at 1:35 p.m. EST today. They are readying the Alpha Magnetic Detector (AMS), the station's cosmic particle detector, for a new cooling system. In this video, Parmitano is guided on the Canadarm2 robotic arm, operated by Flight Engineer Jessica Meir, towards the AMS work site.
